µJEWith Mekka Symposium now officially dead the scene is looking for another party to spend easter. The party calendar showed six parties during easter 2003 with Breakpoint being a new party. Breakpoint was positioned as the follow-up to Mekka Symposium so my expectations were high - this is where I would be heading. I am writing this text a few hours before the Amiga and PC demo compos start and so far I am thoroughly enjoying myself over here.

Zito asked me to write a few words on a topic of my own choosing for the party-issue of Jurassic Park. The graphics compos seemed to be the most appropriate in my case, so here goes...

Judging from the way the graphics compos were organized it was quite obvious that many of the organizers for Mekka were also involved in Breakpoint. Just like at Mekka the graphics were split in a theme compo and a freestyle compo, and just like at Mekka all the graphics were shown twice on the big screen. What was different this time was that some in-between steps (stages) of the images were shown on the big screen as well. This is a great way to see how each image is build up from the beginning until the finished result.

Another difference in this compo was that the images were also zoomed into on the big screen, I have not seen this before at any other party. Usually just the finished result is put on a big screen for a couple of seconds, but now the images were zoomed into as well to show the finer details of the images - this was achieved by one of the organizers using ACDSee (PC) for real-time zooming on the details of the image. This is another nice detail which I liked about the way the graphics compos were organized, although this did introduce a bit of subjectiveness into the way the images were shown. What I mean is that some details (especially on the images with female characters on them) got a little bit more attention than others.

The topic for the theme compo at Breakpoint was "Ice" and boy they couldn't have chosen a more appropriate subject. I am sure you have heard that the first evening at Breakpoint the temperature in the main hall was not very comfortable. As soon as the sun set the temperature started dropping. Several people even suggested renaming the party to Freezepoint at that time. Luckily some extra heating was arranged, so the next evening was a lot better. I heard that the heating used three times more power as all the 800 - 1000 computers combined.

Anyway, onto the graphics, I will mention some of the more interesting graphics in this review.


